The Koenig decomposition for the kinetic energy of a rigid body is: \[\begin{align}
    T = \frac{1}{2}m\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\frac{1}{2}\mathbf{H}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
\end{align}\] In this class, \(\boldsymbol{\omega} = \omega \mathbf{E}_z\), \(\frac{1}{2}\mathbf{H}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega} = \frac{1}{2}I_{zz} w^2\).
In the special case of a fixed point rotation about point \(O\), the kinetic energy becomes \[\begin{align}
    T = \frac{1}{2}\mathbf{H}^O\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
\end{align}\] which simplifies to \(T = \frac{1}{2}I^O_{zz} w^2\) when \(\boldsymbol{\omega} = \omega\mathbf{E}_z\).
The work-energy theorem for a rigid body is: \[\begin{align}
    \frac{dT}{dt} = \mathbf{F}\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\mathbf{M}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega} = \sum_{i=1}^N\mathbf{F}_i\cdot\mathbf{v}_i+\mathbf{M}_e\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
\end{align}\] Integrating the above expression with respect time between \(t_A\) and \(t_B\), we obtain \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        T_B-T_A = W_{\mathbf{F},AB}+W_{\mathbf{M},AB} = \sum_{i=1}^N W_{\mathbf{F}_i,AB}+W_{\mathbf{M}_e,AB},
        \label{eq:work-energy-theorem-RB}
    \end{split}
\end{align}\] where the work of the forces and moments is calculates as follows: \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        W_{\mathbf{F},AB} &= \int_{t_A}^{t_B}\mathbf{F}\cdot\mathbf{v}_Cdt,\\
        W_{\mathbf{M},AB} &= \int_{t_A}^{t_B}\mathbf{M}^C\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega} dt,\\
        W_{\mathbf{F}_i,AB} &= \int_{t_A}^{t_B}\mathbf{F}_i\cdot\mathbf{v}_i dt,\\
        W_{\mathbf{M}_e,AB} &= \int_{t_A}^{t_B}\mathbf{M}_e\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega} dt,\\
    \end{split}
\end{align}\] Notice that in calculating the work of a force, we dot the force with the velocity of its point of application.
As in particles and systems of particles, this theorem can be used to establish conservation of the total energy of a rigid body during a motion.
In the following section, we derive these results.
By definition, the kinetic energy \(T\) of a rigid body is the (continuous) sum of the kinetic energies of the differential masses composing it: \[\begin{align}
    T = \frac{1}{2}\int_{\mathcal{R}}\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{v}\rho dv.
\end{align}\] We can introduce the \(\mathbf{v}_C\) term through \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        & \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{v}_C+\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\boldsymbol{\pi},\\
        & \boldsymbol{\pi} = \mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}_C,\\
        & \boldsymbol{\omega} = \omega_x\mathbf{e}_x+\omega_y\mathbf{e}_y+\omega_z\mathbf{e}_z.
    \end{split}
\end{align}\] Substituting the above expressions in the kinetic energy integral, we get \[\begin{align}
    T = \frac{1}{2}\int_{\mathcal{B}}\left(\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+2\mathbf{v}_C\cdot(\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\boldsymbol{\pi})+(\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\boldsymbol{\pi})\cdot(\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\boldsymbol{\pi})\right) dm
\end{align}\] For the first two terms in the above integral, \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        & \frac{1}{2}\int_{\mathcal{B}}\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C dm = \frac{\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C}{2}\int dm = \frac{1}{2}m\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C.\\
        & \int_{\mathcal{B}}\mathbf{v}_C\cdot(\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\boldsymbol{\pi})dm = \mathbf{v}_C\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\int\pi dm \right) = 0.
    \end{split}
\end{align}\] Thus, \[\begin{align}
    T = \frac{1}{2}m\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\frac{1}{2}\int_{\mathcal{B}}(\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\boldsymbol{\pi})\cdot(\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\boldsymbol{\pi})dm
\end{align}\] we can simplify \[\begin{align}
    (\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\boldsymbol{\pi})\cdot(\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\boldsymbol{\pi}) = ((\boldsymbol{\pi}\cdot\boldsymbol{\pi})\boldsymbol{\omega}-(\boldsymbol{\pi}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega})\cdot\boldsymbol{\pi}).
\end{align}\] Recall that \[\begin{align}
    \mathbf{H}^C = \int_{\mathcal{B}}\boldsymbol{\pi}\times(\omega\times\boldsymbol{\pi})dm = \int_{\mathcal{B}}((\boldsymbol{\pi}\cdot\boldsymbol{\pi})\boldsymbol{\omega}-(\boldsymbol{\pi}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega})\boldsymbol{\pi})dm.
\end{align}\] Hence, we obtain the Koenig decomposition: \[\begin{align}
    T = \frac{1}{2}m\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\frac{1}{2}\mathbf{H}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
\end{align}\]
In the case of fixed point rotation, \(\mathbf{v}_C = \boldsymbol{\omega}\times(\mathbf{r}_C-\mathbf{r}_O)\) and \(\mathbf{v}_O = 0\), then \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        T &= \frac{1}{2}\mathbf{G}\cdot(\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\mathbf{r}_{C/O})+\frac{1}{2}\mathbf{H}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}\\
        &= \frac{1}{2}\boldsymbol{\omega}\cdot(\mathbf{r}_{C/O}\times\mathbf{G})+\frac{1}{2}\mathbf{H}^C\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}\\
        &= \frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{r}_{C/O}\times\mathbf{G}+\mathbf{H})\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}\\
        &= \frac{1}{2}\mathbf{H}^O\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
    \end{split}
\end{align}\]
\[\begin{align}
    \dot{T} = \frac{1}{2}m\dot{\mathbf{v}}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\frac{1}{2}m\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\dot{\mathbf{v}}_C+\frac{1}{2}\dot{\mathbf{H}}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}+\frac{1}{2}\mathbf{H}\cdot\dot{\boldsymbol{\omega}}.
\end{align}\] We need to show that \(\dot{\mathbf{H}}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega} = \mathbf{H}\cdot\dot{\boldsymbol{\omega}}\). \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        \boldsymbol{\alpha} = \dot{\boldsymbol{\omega}} &= \frac{d}{dt}(\omega_x\mathbf{e}_x+\omega_y\mathbf{e}_y+\omega_z\mathbf{e}_z)\\
        &= \dot{\omega}_x\mathbf{e}_x+\dot{\omega}_y\mathbf{e}_y+\dot{\omega}_z\mathbf{e}_z+\omega_x\dot{\mathbf{e}}_x+\omega_y\dot{\mathbf{e}}_y+\omega_z\dot{\mathbf{e}}_z\\
        &= \dot{\omega}_x\mathbf{e}_x+\dot{\omega}_y\mathbf{e}_y+\dot{\omega}_z\mathbf{e}_z+\boldsymbol{\omega}\times(\omega_x\mathbf{e}_x+\omega_y\mathbf{e}_y+\omega_z\mathbf{e}_z)\\
        &= \dot{\omega}_x\mathbf{e}_x+\dot{\omega}_y\mathbf{e}_y+\dot{\omega}_z\mathbf{e}_z.
    \end{split}
\end{align}\]
Another direct calculation using this expression for \(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\) shows that \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        \mathbf{H}^C\cdot\dot{\boldsymbol{\omega}} = (I_{xx}\omega_x+I_{xy}\omega_y+I_{xz}\omega_z)\dot{\omega}_x+(I_{xy}\omega_x+I_{yy}\omega_y+I_{yz}\omega_z)\dot{\omega}_y+(I_{xz}\omega_x+I_{yz}\omega_y+I_{zz}\omega_z)\dot{\omega}_z.
    \end{split}
\end{align}\]
Comparing this to the corresponding expression for \(\dot{H}^C\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}\), we find that they are equal. Consequently, \[\begin{align}
    \dot{T} = \frac{1}{2}m\dot{\mathbf{v}}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\frac{1}{2}m\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\dot{\mathbf{v}}_C+\frac{1}{2}\dot{\mathbf{H}}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}+\frac{1}{2}\dot{\mathbf{H}}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
\end{align}\] This result implies that \[\begin{align}
    \dot{T} = m\dot{\mathbf{v}}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\dot{\mathbf{H}}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
\end{align}\] Invoking the balance of linear momentum and the balance of angular momentum, we obtain the work-energy theorem: \[\begin{align}
    \dot{T} = \mathbf{F}\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\mathbf{M}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
\end{align}\] You should notice how this is a natural extension of the work-energy theorem for a single particle. We can then integrate these expressions of the work-energy theorem to get equation (\(\ref{eq:work-energy-theorem-RB}\)).
Recall, \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        & \mathbf{F} = \sum_{i=1}^K\mathbf{F}_i\\
        & \mathbf{M}^C = \mathbf{M}_e+\sum_{i=1}^K(\mathbf{r}_i-\mathbf{r}_C)\times\mathbf{F}_i
    \end{split}
\end{align}\] Hence, the mechanical power of the resultant forces and moments can be written as \[\begin{align}
    \mathbf{F}\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\mathbf{M}^C\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega} = \left(\sum_{i=1}^K\mathbf{F}_i\right)\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\mathbf{M}_e\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}+\left(\sum_{i=1}^K(\mathbf{x}_i-\mathbf{x}_C)\times\mathbf{F}_i\right)\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}
\end{align}\] With some minor manipulations involving the identity \(\mathbf{a}\cdot(\mathbf{b}\times\mathbf{c}) = \mathbf{c}\cdot(\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b})\) and noting that \(\mathbf{v}_i = \mathbf{v}_C+\boldsymbol{\omega}\times(\mathbf{x}_i-\mathbf{x}_C)\), we find that \[\begin{align}
    \mathbf{F}\cdot\mathbf{v}_C+\mathbf{M}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega} = \sum_{i=1}^K\mathbf{F}_i\cdot\mathbf{v}_i+\mathbf{M}_e\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
\end{align}\] In conclusion, we have an alternative form of the work-energy theorem that proves to be far easier to use in applications: \[\begin{align}
    \dot{T} = \sum_{i=1}^K\mathbf{F}_i\cdot\mathbf{v}_i+\mathbf{M}_e\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}.
\end{align}\]
